pr_body:
Py2.6 compatibility was sacrificed; also 3.2 is known not to work either (mainly because of v2 unicode literals).

I've tried to keep unrelated changes away, but couldn't resist on these:

- There's `boltons.compat.lrange` that always returns a list (makes a lot of code in `statsutils.py` cleaner vs `list(xrange(x))`);
- Saw `print "Deprecation Warning: foo"` and couldn't resist converting to use the `warnings` module;
- Made `six` an install dependency; IMHO it's a better solution than rewriting all of it inside `compat.py`.

I saw a lot of random test code inside `if __name__ == "__main__"`; mostly didn't touch that, this should probably be refactored into real unit tests.

Fixes #195

cc @jbuck 

@jvehent: While doing this I noticed there's a lot of duplication on the JSON and YAML stores to parse the metadata. What do you think of refactoring it so that each store just returns its metadata as a `map[interface{}]interface{}`, and then another method (the same for all trust stores) converts that map into the proper struct?

Now you can run:

    ./pants graph-query --query-file=foo.json ::

To get back a list of targets matching criteria based on their
name, spec, target type, dependencies, dependees, and sources.

For example, you can write a query file that looks like:

    {
      "type": "java_library",
      "not": {
        "dependee": {
          "type": "java_tests"
        }
      }
    }

To find java libraries without corresponding tests.
If you want to not include integration tests, you could try:

    {
      "type": "java_library",
      "not": {
        "dependee": {
          "type": "java_tests",
          "not": {
            "name": "int-.*"
          }
        }
      }
    }

Addressing [issue 170 in angr-doc](https://github.com/angr/angr-doc/issues/170).

Now without enabling `EFFICIENT_STATE_MERGING`, we can still do a semi-optimal state merging: Only `SimStateHistory`s know their ancestors, all other state plugins will be merged as in normal (less optimized) state merging. This might be a good balance between memory usage (we don't have to store a strong reference for all states anymore) and state merging performance.

@zardus @rhelmot Please review and comment. Thanks!

Fixes #2736. Sagi and I worked on this together yesterday.

@SwartzCr would you be able to take a look at this? Basically, the problem was the core client asks for security enhancements per domain but Apache applies them for each vhost. Therefore, if you have two domains in one vhost and ask for a redirect, you'll get a warning on the second one saying you already have a redirect in the vhost.

We fixed this problem by keeping track of the enhancements that were enabled during the current run.
